#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:127
msgid "How sanitizers affect your binaries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:129
msgid ""
"Sanitizers instrument your code at compile time, adding runtime checks and "
"metadata. This changes your binary's **Application Binary Interface (ABI)**, "
"making instrumented code incompatible with non-instrumented code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:132
msgid "**Key changes sanitizers make:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:134
msgid ""
"**Memory layout**: Sanitizers add shadow memory, guard zones, or tracking "
"metadata around your data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:135
msgid ""
"**Function calls**: Standard library functions (``malloc``, ``free``, etc.) "
"are wrapped or intercepted"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:136
msgid ""
"**Runtime dependencies**: Instrumented code requires sanitizer runtime "
"libraries (``libasan``, ``libtsan``, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:137
msgid ""
"**Linking**: Mixing instrumented and non-instrumented code can cause "
"crashes, false positives, or undefined behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:140
msgid "Handling external code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:142
msgid ""
"When using sanitizers, you must consider how to handle third-party "
"dependencies. As mixing instrumented and non-instrumented code can lead to "
"issues, here are some strategies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:145
msgid "**Always require full instrumentation:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:147
msgid "**MemorySanitizer (MSan)**: Changes function ABIs to pass shadow state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:148
msgid ""
"**DataFlowSanitizer (DFSan)**: Explicitly modifies the ABI by appending "
"label parameters to functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:149
msgid ""
"**ThreadSanitizer (TSan)**: Changes memory layout and intercepts "
"synchronization primitives. Some code may not be instrumented by "
"ThreadSanitizer, but not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:152
msgid "**Usually require full instrumentation:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:154
msgid ""
"**AddressSanitizer (ASan)**: Adds redzones and shadow memory; Works with non-"
"instrumented code, but not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:155
msgid ""
"**HardwareAddressSanitizer (HWASan)**: Similar to ASan but uses hardware "
"tagging. Mixing is possible but not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:157
msgid "**Can often mix with non-instrumented code:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:159
msgid ""
"**UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer (UBSan)**: Adds runtime checks for undefined "
"behavior; Minimal ABI changes, safer to mix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:160
msgid ""
"**LeakSanitizer (LSan)**: Detects memory leaks at program exit; When "
"standalone, has minimal ABI impact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:162
msgid ""
"For reliable results, **always** rebuild your entire dependency tree with "
"the same sanitizer configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:165
msgid "Enabling Sanitizers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:167
msgid ""
"Conan cannot infer sanitizer flags from settings automatically. You have to "
"pass the appropriate compiler and linker flags (e.g., ``-fsanitize=`` or ``/"
"fsanitize=address``) via profiles or toolchains. Conan toolchains (e.g., "
"``CMakeToolchain``, ``MesonToolchain``) will propagate flags defined in "
"``[conf]`` sections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:172
msgid "Modeling and applying sanitizers using settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:174
msgid ""
"If you want to model sanitizer options so that the package ID is affected by "
"them, you can :ref:`customize new compiler sub-settings "
"<reference_config_files_customizing_settings>`. You should not need to "
"modify ``settings.yml`` directly; instead add :ref:`the settings_user.yml "
"<examples_config_files_settings_user>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:178
msgid ""
"This approach is preferred because enabling a sanitizer alters the package "
"ID, allowing you to build and use the same binary package with or without "
"sanitizers. This is ideal for development and debugging workflows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:182
msgid "Configuring sanitizers as part of settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:184
msgid ""
"If you typically use a specific set of sanitizers or combinations for your "
"builds, you can specify a sub-setting as a list of values in your "
"``settings_user.yml``. For example, for Clang, GCC and MSVC:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:187
msgid "settings_user.yml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:187
msgid ""
"compiler:\n"
"   clang:\n"
"     sanitizer: [null, Address, Leak, Thread, Memory, UndefinedBehavior, "
"HardwareAssistanceAddress, KernelAddress, AddressUndefinedBehavior, "
"ThreadUndefinedBehavior]\n"
"   gcc:\n"
"     sanitizer: [null, Address, Leak, Thread, UndefinedBehavior, "
"KernelAddress, AddressUndefinedBehavior, ThreadUndefinedBehavior]\n"
"   msvc:\n"
"     sanitizer: [null, Address, KernelAddress]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:199
msgid ""
"This example defines a few common sanitizers. You can add any sanitizer your "
"compiler supports. The ``null`` value represents a build without sanitizers. "
"The above models for Clang the use of ``-fsanitize=address``, ``-"
"fsanitize=thread``, ``-fsanitize=memory``, ``-fsanitize=leak``, ``-"
"fsanitize=undefined``, ``-fsanitize=hwaddress``, ``-fsanitize=kernel-"
"address``, as well as combinations like ``-fsanitize=address,undefined`` and "
"``-fsanitize=thread,undefined``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:204
msgid ""
"As the ``sanitizer`` setting is a list, it can be choose by one single value "
"at time. As an workaround to support mutiple sanitizers at same time, you "
"can define combinations like ``AddressUndefinedBehavior`` and "
"``ThreadUndefinedBehavior``, as listed above. There is no limitation on the "
"number of combinations you can define, but keep in mind that these are only "
"tags to help you manage your builds. You still need to pass the appropriate "
"flags to the compiler and linker accordingly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:211
msgid "Adding sanitizers as part of the profile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:213
msgid ""
"Another option is to add the sanitizer values as part of a profile. This "
"way, you can easily switch between different configurations by using "
"dedicated profiles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:216
msgid "compiler_sanitizers/profiles/gcc_asan"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:216
msgid ""
"[settings]\n"
"arch=x86_64\n"
"os=Linux\n"
"build_type=Debug\n"
"compiler=gcc\n"
"compiler.cppstd=gnu20\n"
"compiler.libcxx=libstdc++11\n"
"compiler.version=15\n"
"compiler.sanitizer=Address\n"
"\n"
"[conf]\n"
"tools.build:cflags+=[\"-fsanitize=address\", \"-fno-omit-frame-pointer\"]\n"
"tools.build:cxxflags+=[\"-fsanitize=address\", \"-fno-omit-frame-pointer\"]\n"
"tools.build:exelinkflags+=[\"-fsanitize=address\"]\n"
"tools.build:sharedlinkflags+=[\"-fsanitize=address\"]\n"
"\n"
"[runenv]\n"
"ASAN_OPTIONS=\"halt_on_error=1:detect_leaks=1\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:238
msgid ""
"For Visual Studio (MSVC) we can obtain an equivalent profile for "
"AddressSanitizer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:240
msgid "compiler_sanitizers/profiles/msvc_asan"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:240
msgid ""
"[settings]\n"
"arch=x86_64\n"
"os=Windows\n"
"build_type=Debug\n"
"compiler=msvc\n"
"compiler.version=194\n"
"compiler.runtime=dynamic\n"
"compiler.runtime_type=Release\n"
"compiler.sanitizer=Address\n"
"\n"
"[conf]\n"
"tools.build:cxxflags+=[\"/fsanitize=address\", \"/Zi\"]\n"
"tools.build:exelinkflags+=[\"/fsanitize=address\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:257
msgid ""
"The Conan client is not capable of deducing the necessary flags from the "
"settings and applying them automatically during the build process. It is "
"necessary to pass the expected sanitizer flags according to the ``compiler."
"sanitizer`` value as part of the compiler and linker flags. Conan's built-in "
"toolchains (like ``CMakeToolchain`` and ``MesonToolchain``) will "
"automatically pick up the flags defined in the ``[conf]`` section and apply "
"them to the build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:264
msgid "Managing sanitizers with a CMake toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:266
msgid ""
"Besides using Conan profiles to manage sanitizer settings, you can also use "
"other approaches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:268
msgid ""
"If you already have a :ref:`custom CMake toolchain file "
"<conan_cmake_user_toolchain>` to manage compiler and build options, you can "
"pass the necessary flags to enable sanitizers there instead of profiles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:271
msgid "cmake/my_toolchain.cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:271
msgid ""
"# Apply to all targets; consider per-target options for finer control\n"
"set(CMAKE_C_FLAGS \"${CMAKE_C_FLAGS} -fsanitize=address,undefined -fno-omit-"
"frame-pointer\")\n"
"set(CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS \"${CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS} -fsanitize=address,undefined -fno-"
"omit-frame-pointer\")\n"
"set(CMAKE_EXE_LINKER_FLAGS \"${CMAKE_EXE_LINKER_FLAGS} -fsanitize=address,"
"undefined\")\n"
"set(CMAKE_SHARED_LINKER_FLAGS \"${CMAKE_SHARED_LINKER_FLAGS} -"
"fsanitize=address,undefined\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:280
msgid "Then, specify this toolchain file as part of your Conan profile:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:282
msgid "profiles/gcc_asan_ubsan"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:282
msgid ""
"[settings]\n"
"arch=x86_64\n"
"os=Linux\n"
"build_type=Debug\n"
"compiler=gcc\n"
"compiler.cppstd=gnu20\n"
"compiler.libcxx=libstdc++11\n"
"compiler.version=15\n"
"compiler.sanitizer=AddressUndefinedBehavior\n"
"\n"
"[conf]\n"
"tools.cmake.cmaketoolchain:user_toolchain=cmake/my_toolchain.cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:298
msgid ""
"This way, you can keep your existing CMake toolchain file and still leverage "
"Conan profiles to manage other settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../security/sanitizers.rst:300
msgid ""
"Note that this approach only works if all dependencies are built using CMake "
"and the ``CMakeToolchain`` integration. If you have dependencies using other "
"build systems (e.g., Meson, Autotools), those dependencies will not receive "
"the sanitizer flags defined in your custom CMake toolchain file."
msgstr ""

